'''Michael Richard''' "'''Micky'''" '''Adams''' (born 8 November 1961) is an [[English people|English]] former professional [[association football|footballer]] turned football manager, who is in charge of [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]]. As a player he was a [[Defender (association football)#Full back|full back]], and made a total of 438 league appearances in a nineteen year professional career in [[the Football League]], including five years with [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] at the highest level. He began his managerial career as player-manager for [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in 1994 and has lead several teams at varying levels with mixed success, being named Manager of the Season twice, and sacked a number of times.

Born in [[Sheffield]], Adams was part of the youth team at [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] from the age of twelve until released in 1977. He turned professional at the Third Division team [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] in 1979, where he  established himself in the first team, winning a move in 1983 to [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] who were in the First Division. He spent four years at Coventry before being sold on to [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] in 1987. He was bought by Southampton for <U+00A3>250,000 in 1989, where he enjoyed five years of top-flight football. He was loaned out to [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] in 1994, before he signed with Fulham later in the year. Appointed as Fulham's player-manager in March 1996, he led the club out of the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] in [[1996<U+2013>97 in English football|1996<U+2013>97]], and was named as the Third Division Manager of the Season. Sacked by Fulham despite his success, he walked out on [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] after less than two weeks in charge, and instead took charge at [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] in November 1997. He was sacked after the club were relegated at the end of the season. At this point he ended his playing career.

He joined [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] as assistant manager, taking charge for one [[Premier League]] game in a caretaker capacity. He returned to management with [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in April 1999. He led the club to the Third Division title in [[2000<U+2013>01 in English football|2000<U+2013>01]], winning the division's Manager of the Season award for a second time. He then moved to [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] as an assistant, before finally being named as the club's manager in April 2002. He took the club to the Premier League as [[Football League First Division|First Division]] runners-up in [[2002<U+2013>03 in English football|2002<U+2013>03]], though he tendered his resignation in October 2004, having failed to keep the club in the top-flight. He took charge at former club Coventry City in January 2005, though lost his job in January 2007 after failing to take the club out of the [[Football League Championship|Championship]]. He returned to Brighton in May 2008, though his second spell in charge would only last nine months. He was appointed as manager of Port Vale in June 2009, before he departed for Sheffield United in December 2010, with Vale heading for promotion out of League Two. He failed to prevent United being relegated into [[Football League One|League One]], and so was sacked in May 2011; this enabled him to return to Port Vale as manager, who had failed poorly in his absence. He has been married twice and has four daughters.

==Playing career==
Adams was born in [[Sheffield]], and was an associate schoolboy with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] from the age of twelve,<ref name="su" /> where his boyhood idol was [[Tony Currie (footballer)|Tony Currie]].<ref name="cn" /> He was a favourite of manager [[Jimmy Sirrel]], though Adams was released from the youth set-up a few months after [[Harry Haslam (footballer)|Harry Haslam]] replaced Sirrel as manager in September 1977.<ref name="su">{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Adams-goes-roots-Blades-return/article-1238941-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Adams goes back to his roots with a Blades return|last=Shaw|first=Steve|date=11 August 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=11 August 2009}}</ref> United's youth team coach John Shaw also left the club and became a coach at [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], and so Adams then travelled 240&nbsp;miles out from home to join Gillingham as an apprentice in August 1978.<ref name="up close">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/leicester/content/articles/2004/08/19/micky_adams_in_depth_interview_feature.shtml|title=Micky Adams up close|date=19 August 2004|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 October 2011}}</ref> During his time as an apprentice he won four caps for the [[England national youth football team|England youth team]], and competed in a tournament in [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]].<ref name="up close" /> He went on to sign as a professional at Gillingham in November 1979. Due to his natural pace, Adams started his playing career as a [[Outside forward|left-winger]] before being converted into a left-back after he was found to lack the technical skill necessary to beat opponents.<ref name = "ITN">{{cite book| title=In That Number <U+2013> A post-war chronicle of Southampton FC |last= Holley |first= Duncan |coauthors= Chalk, Gary | publisher=[[Hagiology Publishing|Hagiology]] | year=2003 | isbn=978-0-9534474-3-5|page=472}}</ref><ref name="up close" /> Coming through the club's ranks at the same time as [[Steve Bruce]], Adams later cited [[Bill Collins (footballer)|Buster Collins]] as a major influence upon his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Port-Vale-Adams-reveals-special-affection-Gillingham/article-2764950-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Adams reveals special affection for Gillingham|last=Shaw|first=Steve|date=16 October 2010|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref><ref name="Buster">{{cite web| title = Adams and Bruce were Buster's premier pupils | publisher = Daily Telegraph| accessdate =2007-09-27 | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2004/03/07/sfnpb207.xml|date=2004-03-06|author=Patrick Barclay |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071118132027/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2004/03/07/sfnpb207.xml|archivedate = 2007-11-18}}</ref>

After 103 appearances for [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] Gillingham he moved on to top-flight [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] in 1983 for a fee between <U+00A3>75,000 and <U+00A3>85,000.<ref name="Sentinel" /><ref>{{cite book | first=Roger|last= Triggs | title=The Men Who Made Gillingham Football Club| publisher=Tempus Publishing Ltd | year=2001| isbn=978-0-7524-2243-5|page=38}}</ref> He struggled with injury during his time at [[Highfield Road]], and was never popular with the fans.<ref name="up close" /> Despite this he managed to play over 100 games for City over a four year period before [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] manager [[Billy Bremner]] took him to the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] for a <U+00A3>110,000 fee. Near the end of his first season at Leeds he played in the club's [[FA Cup Semi-finals|FA Cup Semi-final]] defeat to former club Coventry at [[Hillsborough Stadium|Hillsborough]], as Coventry won 3<U+2013>2 in extra time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/page/OnThisWeek/0,,10269~1030058,00.html|title=Hillsborough History|date=26 May 2007|work=ccfc.co.uk|accessdate=2 October 2011}}</ref> Leeds suffered further heartbreak in 1987 by losing the [[1987 Football League Second Division play-off Final|play-off Final]] to [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], again after extra time. His return to [[Football League First Division|First Division]] football instead came in March 1989 when [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] offered Leeds <U+00A3>250,000 for his services.<ref name="Sentinel">{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/sport/Micky-Adams-career-far/article-1051975-detail/article.html|title=Micky Adams career so far|date=4 June 2009 |work=The Sentinel|accessdate=4 June 2009}}</ref> Adams made his debut for the "Saints" on 25 March 1989, taking [[Derek Statham]]'s place at left-back in a 3<U+2013>1 defeat by [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. Adams retained his place for the next seven games, before losing out to [[Gerry Forrest]] for the last few matches of the season.<ref>{{cite book| title=In That Number <U+2013> A post-war chronicle of Southampton FC |last=  |first=  | publisher= | year= | isbn= |page=206}}</ref> Adams played the first seven matches of [[1989<U+2013>90 in English football|the 1989<U+2013>90 season]] before losing his place through injury to [[Francis Benali]], who then began to form a useful full-back partnership with [[Jason Dodd]]. In April 1990, Adams was recalled alongside new signing [[Oleksiy Cherednyk]] and they played out the remainder of the season together.<ref>{{cite book| title=In That Number <U+2013> A post-war chronicle of Southampton FC |last=  |first=  | publisher= | year= | isbn= |page=213}}</ref>

Adams began to establish himself as the first-choice left-back at the start of [[1990<U+2013>91 in English football|the 1990<U+2013>91 season]], partnered first by Cherednyk and then Dodd, and finally by [[Barry Horne (footballer)|Barry Horne]] on the right.<ref>{{cite book| title=In That Number <U+2013> A post-war chronicle of Southampton FC |last=  |first=  | publisher= | year= | isbn= |page=219}}</ref> Once he had overcome the niggling injuries of his first two seasons at [[The Dell (Southampton)|The Dell]], Adams' consistency began to ensure that the left-back position was more or less his own, with his energetic forays along the touchline helping to give the side an extra cutting edge.<ref name = "ITN"/> His first goals for the Saints came in [[1991<U+2013>92 in English football|the 1991<U+2013>92 season]] against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{cite book| title=In That Number <U+2013> A post-war chronicle of Southampton FC |last=  |first=  | publisher= | year= | isbn= |page=223}}</ref> Against West Ham on 14 April 1992, he scored the only goal with a far-post volley in the 88th minute after [[Matthew Le Tissier]] had created space to whip over a cross: the goal was described as "a moment of true class in an otherwise ordinary game".<ref>{{cite book| title=In That Number <U+2013> A post-war chronicle of Southampton FC |last=  |first=  | publisher= | year= | isbn= |page=222}}</ref>

During [[1992<U+2013>93 FA Premier League|the inaugural season]] of the [[Premier League]], Adams missed only four games, making 38 appearances with four goals, with his right-wing partner now being [[Jeff Kenna]], with manager [[Ian Branfoot]] playing Dodd and Benali further forward.<ref>{{cite book| title=In That Number <U+2013> A post-war chronicle of Southampton FC |last=  |first=  | publisher= | year= | isbn= |page=228}}</ref> He wrote himself into the history books, for all the wrong reasons, when he was sent off for dissent on 19 August 1992 against [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] at [[Loftus Road]], during the second game of the season.<ref>{{cite book| title=In That Number <U+2013> A post-war chronicle of Southampton FC |last=  |first=  | publisher= | year= | isbn= |page=224}}</ref> His was the first ever red card in the Premiership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orange.co.uk/sport/football/6057_pr.htm|title=Ask the Gaffer football trivia archive|work=orange.co.uk|accessdate=16 August 2009}}</ref> The [[1993<U+2013>94 FA Premier League|1993<U+2013>94]] Premiership season was Adams' last in the top flight; he started the season as the preferred choice at left-back before losing out to [[Simon Charlton]]. He featured in 19 out of 42 league games that season as Southampton finished 18th and narrowly avoided relegation. His final game for Southampton came in a 1<U+2013>0 defeat at home to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], immediately following which Branfoot was sacked as manager, to be replaced by [[Alan Ball, Jr.|Alan Ball]].<ref>{{cite book| title=In That Number <U+2013> A post-war chronicle of Southampton FC |last=  |first=  | publisher= | year= | isbn= |page=235}}</ref> Adams never played under Ball and was loaned out to [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] in March 1994 until the end of the season.<ref name = "ITN"/> He scored three goals in ten games for the "Potters", but did not join the club on a permanent basis as the management staff refused to allow him to help out as a coach at the club's academy.<ref name="up close" /> In his five years with Southampton, Adams made a total of 174 first-team appearances, scoring seven goals.<ref name = "ITN"/>

In July 1994, he joined [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on a free transfer where he was reunited with Ian Branfoot in preparation for the "Cottagers" [[1994<U+2013>95 Fulham F.C. season|1994<U+2013>95 season]]. Fulham had just been relegated to Division Three (the bottom tier of the professional league) for the first time in their history. He signed with the club on the understanding that Branfoot would teach him the ropes of coaching.<ref name="up close" /> They finished seventh in the league that season, but due to a restructuring of the league which saw one less promotion place in the three lower divisions, Fulham missed out on a play-off place. When Branfoot became general manager in March 1996, Adams was appointed player-manager of a Fulham side on course for their lowest ever finish <U+2013> 17th in Division Three.

==Managerial career==
Before going into management, the "straight-talking [[Yorkshire]]man"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/lmatv/interview-3786.html|title=Adams aims to upset the odds|date=21 July 2003|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> had already demonstrated his ability to spot talented youngsters. Around 1994 he spotted [[Wayne Bridge]] playing for Olivers Battery; he recommended Bridge to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], who then signed him as a trainee in July 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-Fresh-start-players-says-Adams/article-1060991-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Fresh start for players, says Adams|last=Shaw|first=Steve|date=9 June 2009|work=The Sentinel |accessdate=9 June 2009}}</ref>

===Fulham===
Adams moved into management with [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], taking over from [[Ian Branfoot]] in March 1996 with the London club languishing in 91st place in the league pyramid.<ref name="up close" /> After he had helped the club avoid non-league football, Fulham were promoted to Division Two as runners-up in the following season's final table,<ref name="ESPN" /> and Adams was given the Third Division Manager of the Season award. He built his side on free transfers and small fees, installing belief and self-confidence in the players at his disposal rather than spending big money.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/Club/ClubHistory/Managers/MickyAdams.aspx|title=Micky Adams|work=fulhamfc.com|accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref> The highest fee he spent on a player during his reign was <U+00A3>200,000 for former "Saints" teammate [[Paul Moody (footballer)|Paul Moody]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-3862.html|title=Adams ready for Roman's empire|date=22 August 2003|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>

Following [[Mohamed Al-Fayed]]'s takeover of Fulham, Adams was dismissed as manager in September 1997 in favour of the higher profile combination of [[Kevin Keegan]] (director of football) and [[Ray Wilkins]] (head coach).<ref name="ESPN">{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/manager?id=23&&cc=5739|title=Micky Adams|last=Johnson|first=Dale|work=ESPN|accessdate=5 June 2009}} {{dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref>

{{quote|"I have to say that it was probably the right decision because look where they are now. All Mr Fayed has to say is 'there's my record'. At the time getting rid of me was a harsh decision. A director at the club told me I was going to be the [[Alex Ferguson]] of Fulham. I signed a five-year contract... and four months later I was sacked."|Adams speaking in July 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-McParland-require-skin-says-Adams/article-1198753-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: McParland will require thick skin, says Adams|date=28 July 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=28 July 2009}}</ref>}}

===Swansea to Brentford to Nottingham===
Shortly after his dismissal from Fulham, Adams made a quick return to management with [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] in Division Three, but left after thirteen days and three matches in charge. Adams claimed that the money he had been promised to strengthen the team had not been forthcoming.<ref name="ESPN" />

Before 1997 was out, Adams took his third job of the [[1997<U+2013>98 in English football|1997<U+2013>98 season]] when he was named manager of [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]. The club had suffered a slump in league form after losing the previous season's Division Two [[1997 Football League Second Division play-off Final|play-off final]], and were struggling near the foot of the table. He signed striker [[Andy Scott (English footballer)|Andy Scott]] from [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] for a fee of <U+00A3>75,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Port-Vale-Scott-ready-lock-horns-boss/story-13438795-detail/story.html|title=Port Vale: Scott ready to lock horns with former boss|date=30 September 2011|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=30 September 2011}}</ref> Despite Adams' efforts, Brentford were [[promotion and relegation|relegated]] to Division Three on the last day of the season, and the club was bought out by [[Ron Noades]], who installed himself as the new Brentford manager.<ref name="CT" />

After taking a break from the game, Adams joined [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] as assistant manager under [[Dave Bassett]]. Bassett was dismissed in January 1999 and so Adams took charge as [[caretaker manager]] for a single [[Premier League|Premiership]] match, before [[Ron Atkinson]] was appointed as Bassett's replacement.<ref name="ESPN" />

===Brighton===
Adams returned to management in April 1999 with Division Three team [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]. The club were in the middle of a financial crisis, which had seen the board sell the [[Goldstone Ground]] just to stay afloat; on the pitch the club were facing a battle for their league status.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-312.html|title=High flying Seagulls delight Adams |date=15 March 2001|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> His first full season as manager was a matter of consolidation as the club finished a respectable 11th, whilst Adams signed talent such as star striker [[Bobby Zamora]].<ref name="ESPN" /> The <U+00A3>100,000 spent on Zamora was the only transfer outlay Adams made in building his squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-547.html|title= Micky Adams is named Division Three winner |date=22 May 2001 |work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>

In his second season as manager, [[2000<U+2013>01 in English football|2000<U+2013>01]], Adams guided Brighton to promotion as Division Three champions after the club had spent five seasons in the league's basement division. A late chase for the title proved to be unnecessary,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-355.html|title= Adams hoping to catch Chesterfield |date=23 March 2001|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> as high flying Chesterfield were deducted nine points for financial irregularities,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-467.html|title= Micky and Nicky promoted |date=2 May 2001|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> leaving Brighton ten points clear at the season's end. He was named as Third Division Manager of the season for a second time, also picking up the [[Football League Third Division Manager of the Month|Third Division Manager of the Month]] award in September 2000.

Adams was clear about his ambitions at managing at a higher level, stating his disappointment at not being offered the management positions at either [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] or [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in the summer of 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-711.html|title=Adams sad to miss Premier interviews|date=16 July 2001|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> He did leave "Seagulls" in October 2001, though by then he had already set the foundations for Brighton to achieve a second successive promotion as Division Two champions in [[2001<U+2013>02 in English football|2001<U+2013>02]]. Over the summer he had brought in players such as [[Simon Morgan]], [[Geoff Pitcher]], [[Robbie Pethick]] and [[Dirk Lehmann]], to give Brighton depth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-1002.html|title=Selfless squad suits Seagulls|date=20 September 2001|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>

===Leicester===
In October 2001 Adams left Brighton to become assistant manager to [[Dave Bassett]] at [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{Cite news| title= Adams quits Brighton| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brighton/1590911.stm| publisher= BBC Sport| date= 10 October 2001| accessdate= 22 July 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title= Bassett becomes Foxes boss| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leicester_city/1590280.stm| publisher= BBC Sport| date= 10 October 2001| accessdate= 22 July 2007}}</ref> [[Peter Taylor (footballer born 1953)|Peter Taylor]], the former Leicester manager, was drafted in to complete Brighton's promotion campaign. Adams chose the move in an attempt to get closer to his dream of managing a [[Premier League|Premiership]] club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-1101.html|title=Adams quits Albion To join Foxes|date=10 October 2001|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> He understood that Bassett was to move 'upstairs' at the end of [[2001<U+2013>02 in English football|the season]], leaving Adams free to take the management job for [[2002<U+2013>03 in English football|2002<U+2013>03]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-1945.html|title=Adams adamant on bossing Foxes|date=15 March 2002|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>

Adams spent six months working under Bassett, during which time Leicester were almost permanently stuck to the bottom of the Premier League table. In March 2002 he demanded the management position for the next season, though he later apologised for his comments and insisted he was happy working under Bassett,<ref name="ESPN" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-1969.html|title=Adams clears up mix-up |date=20 March 2002|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> and had no regrets about leaving Brighton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-1974.html|title=Adams rubbishes talk of regrets |date=21 March 2002|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> The next month, just before relegation was confirmed,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-2108.html|title= Adams <U+2013> My work starts now |date=12 April 2002|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Adams was promoted to the manager's seat while Bassett became Director of Football.<ref>{{Cite news| title= Leicester appoint Adams| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leicester_city/1910438.stm| publisher= BBC Sport| date= 4 April 2002| accessdate= 22 July 2007}}</ref> Adams said: "I'm not expecting to produce a miracle, I'm still working with the same group of players".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-2065.html|title=Leicester name Adams as new boss|date= 4 April 2002|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>

In July 2002 he appointed [[Alan Cork]] as his number two.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-2504.html|title=Cork plugs the gap at Leicester |date=28 June 2002|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Losing just one of their opening eleven games, his side made an excellent start to the campaign, seeing Adams rewarded with the [[Football League First Division Manager of the Month|Manager of the Month award]] for September 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-2865.html|title=Foxes boss gets September gong |date=1 October 2002|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Despite Leicester going into receivership with debts of <U+00A3>30 million and being banned from the transfer market until a takeover was completed,<ref name="CT" /> Adams was able to guide them to promotion back to the Premiership at the first attempt<U+2014>they ended the 2002<U+2013>03 season as Division One runners-up behind champions [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]. At the end of the campaign he signed a new three year contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-3701.html |title=Adams signs new deal with Foxes|date=30 May 2003|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>

{{Quote|"I have a lot of respect for Micky Adams, who has proved himself at all levels. He has gone into clubs with little or no money to spend and shown he is not afraid of taking on tough jobs. I wish him well in the future, because he is one of the brightest young managers in the game."|[[Kevin Keegan]] speaking in November 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-4090.html |title=Keegan admits Adams admiration|date=10 November 2003|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>}}

He was in charge for the first game at the [[King Power Stadium|Walkers Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-3737.html|title=Adams delight at Foxes' home start|date=19 June 2003|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Despite a good start to their campaign,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/lmatv/interview-4148.html|title=Micky's managerial mindset|date=2 December 2003|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> the club fell into the relegation zone in the new year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-4318.html|title=Adams vows to fight on |date= 3 February 2004|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Adams was clearly resentful of lucrative long term contracts dealt out to his less talented players by previous managers, which restricted his ability to bring in fresh faces to boost their campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-4414.html|title=Micky defends his 'Misfits'|date=3 March 2004|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Leicester slipped back down again in [[2003<U+2013>04 in English football|2003<U+2013>04]] to 18th place, bracketed together with the two other relegated sides <U+2014> [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] and [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] <U+2014> whose goal difference was inferior to Leicester's. The "Foxes" were becoming a "yo-yo club" and Adams blamed this on a lack of investment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-4525.html|title=Adams sees further ups and downs|date=14 April 2004|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> During March 2004 nine Leicester players were arrested for various offences related to a drunken outing that ended with an alleged sexual assault on three German tourists,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/l/leicester_city/3532059.stm|title=Nine Leicester players held|date=4 March 2004|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/scottish-players-arrested-over-sex-charges-footballers-held-in-spain-1.91716|title=Scottish players arrested over sex charges Footballers held in Spain |last=Simpson|first=Cameron|date=5 March 2004|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref> with three players being charged: [[Paul Dickov]], [[Frank Sinclair]] and [[Keith Gillespie]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/l/leicester_city/3518818.stm|title=Adams mulls over trio's return|date=17 March 2004|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Boss+says+%60My+boys+are+innocent%27.-a0114045707|title=Boss says `My boys are innocent'.|date=9 March 2004|work=Daily Record|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref> The three faced up to fourteen years in prison if found guilty of rape, and the trio's bail totalled <U+00A3>196,500.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/leicestershire/3503880.stm|title=Leicester footballers back in UK|date=12 March 2004|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref> The club had already been rocked by various incidents on overseas tours over years, with [[Stan Collymore]] arrested for setting off a fire extinguisher in 2000, and [[Dennis Wise]] breaking [[Callum Davidson]]'s jaw in a row over a card game in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3a+LEICESTER%3a+A+CLUB+ON+ITS+KNEES%3b+PREMIERSHIP+ROCKED+BY+NEW...-a0113959549|title=Football: I'll fight on vows boss Adams.|last=Rodgers|first=Martin|date=6 March 2004|work=The Mirror|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref> Adams had previously initiated a crackdown in club discipline, going so far as to enforce random breathalyser tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3a+DON%27T+GO%3b+EXCLUSIVE+Leicester+players%27+plea+to+under-fire...-a0113989959|title=Leicester players' plea to under-fire boss Adams.|last=Lewis|first=Darren|date=8 March 2004|work=The Mirror|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref> Adams said that "in a lot of people's eyes, the players are guilty before they have had a fair trial - which is not the case".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leicester_city/3497720.stm|title=Leicester trio to miss out|date=12 March 2004|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref> The incident also cast doubt over Adams' future at the club,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/3534979.stm|title=The gossip column|date=5 March 2004|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/3540133.stm|title=The gossip column|date=7 March 2004|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref> as reports surfaced that he planned to quit the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leicester_city/3540673.stm|title=Leicester back Adams|date=7 March 2004|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref> He did in fact offer his resignation, which was rejected by the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/I+offered+to+quit%2c+says+boss+Adams.-a0114045772|title=I offered to quit, says boss Adams.|date=9 March 2004|work=Daily Record|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+ADAMS+AGONY%3B+EXCLUSIVE+Leicester+boss+on+brink+of+quitting.-a0113978896|title=Leicester boss on brink of quitting.|last=Smith|first=Paul|date=7 March 2004|work=Sunday Mirror|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref> However he kept faith in his players' innocence,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/l/leicester_city/3515184.stm|title=Adams slams football unions|date=16 March 2004|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref> and claimed "if they are guilty of anything it is of being unprofessional - of being drunk to excess".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Sex+case+players%27+boss+offered+to+go.-a0114033048|title=Sex case players' boss offered to go|last=Wells|first=Jacqui|date=9 March 2004|work=The Journal|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref> His faith was later vindicated when it transpired that all allegations against the players were false.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/real_story/3740807.stm|title=Footballer haunted by false rape claim|date=23 May 2004|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref>

The club lost their talismanic [[Turkish people|Turk]] [[Muzzy Izzet]] in the summer of 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-4585.html|title=Adams concedes Izzet exit |date= 6 May 2004|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Adams had previously stated his concern that they would be unable to regain their top tier status before he resigned as Leicester manager in October 2004,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-4574.html|title=Adams fears for the future |date=1 May 2004|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> after a poor start to the [[Football League Championship|Championship]] campaign dashed the club's hopes of an instant return to the Premiership.<ref>{{Cite news| title= Adams resigns as Leicester boss| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leicester_city/3732754.stm| publisher= BBC Sport| date= 11 October 2004| accessdate= 22 July 2007}}</ref>

{{Quote|"This is a very sad day for Leicester City Football Club. Everyone connected with the club wanted Micky to stay and we did our utmost to try to persuade him to change his mind."|Leicester City Chief executive Tim Davies on announcing Adams' departure.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-4803.html|title=Adams resigns as Leicester boss|date=11 October 2004|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>}}

===Coventry City===
In January 2005, Adams made a return to management in the Championship with struggling [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], a club he had been at during his playing career.<ref>{{Cite news| title= Adams named as Coventry manager| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/coventry_city/4193941.stm| publisher= BBC Sport| date= 21 January 2005| accessdate= 22 July 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-4876.html|title=Coventry appoint Adams |date=21 January 2005|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Adams managed to save the club from relegation by the end of [[2004<U+2013>05 in English football|the season]], winning the [[Football League Championship Manager of the Month]] award for April in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-4955.html|title=Adams wins two awards in the week |date=6 May 2005 |work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>

He was expected by some to mount a challenge for promotion to the Premiership in [[2005<U+2013>06 Coventry City F.C. season|2005<U+2013>06]], which was the club's first season in the new [[Ricoh Arena]]. The team started out poorly, but improved in the second half of the season to rise up the table, with Adams making an inspired signing in [[Dennis Wise]].<ref name="CT" /> However, despite excellent home form, he could only guide Coventry as high as 8th, missing out on a play-off place by only two league places, though several points adrift of that year's standard.

Midway through the [[2006<U+2013>07 Coventry City F.C. season|following season]] however, following a run of five games without defeat, Coventry suddenly and unexpectedly hit a bad run of form. A 5<U+2013>0 defeat at [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] began a sequence of eight games without a win, including six defeats. This culminated in a 2<U+2013>0 home defeat to [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] in the [[FA Cup]], a game which also saw a record low attendance at the Ricoh Arena. On 17 January 2007, the day after the cup exit, the club parted company with Adams, with Coventry lying 16th in the Championship.<ref name="CT">{{cite web|url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/coventry-city-fc/coventry-city-fc-news/tm_headline=factfile--micky-adams&method=full&objectid=18490990&siteid=50003-name_page.html|title=Factfile: Micky Adams|last=Smith|first=Martin|date=17 January 2007|work=Coventry Telegraph|accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref> Adams stated that he intended to return to management as soon as possible.<ref>{{Cite news| title= Adams sacked as Coventry manager| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/coventry_city/6270295.stm| publisher= BBC Sport| date= 17 January 2007| accessdate= 22 July 2007}}</ref> He admitted that the sale of [[Gary McSheffrey]] to [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] had been a turning point in the club's season, but also said that "I genuinely believe that I could have turned it around" and "I tried my best and that's all I can do."<ref name="could have">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Adams%3A+I+could%27ve+turned+it+around%3B+%2B%2B%2B+MICKY+ADAMS+SACKING.-a0157846197|title=Adams: I could've turned it around|last=Turner|first=Andy|date=18 January 2007|work=Coventry Evening Telegraph|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref>

{{Quote|"We are committed to our three-year quest to get Coventry City back into the Premiership and believe that tough decisions like this will sometimes be needed to fulfil that aim as is sadly the case today.|Coventry City statement following Adams' dismissal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-5680.html|title=Adams departs Ricoh |date=17 January 2007|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>}}

===Colchester and return to Brighton===
In July 2007, Adams was appointed by [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] as assistant manager to [[Geraint Williams]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-5850.html|title=Adams joins Colchester |date=14 July 2007|work=LMA|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> replacing [[Mick Harford]] who had left the previous month.<ref>{{Cite news| title= Adams given Colchester position| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/colchester_united/6898825.stm| publisher= BBC Sport| date=  14 July 2007| accessdate= 22 July 2007}}</ref> He subsequently left this role in January 2008, stating that he wanted to return to management.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/colchester_united/7174909.stm|title=Adams leaves job with Colchester |date=7 January 2008|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 June 2009}}</ref>

In May 2008, Adams returned to the helm at Brighton & Hove Albion,<ref>{{Cite news| title= Return of the Special One| url= http://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/albion/albionnews/display.var.2258434.0.return_of_the_special_one.php| publisher= The Argus (Brighton UK)| date= 9 May 2008| accessdate= 9 May 2008}}</ref> supplanting [[Dean Wilkins]]. On 21 February 2009, Adams left the club by "mutual consent", (although he had stated he wished to stay) due to poor team performances.<ref>{{Cite news| title= Brighton part company with Adams | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brighton/7903287.stm| publisher= [[BBC Sport]]| date= 21 February 2009| accessdate= 21 February 2009|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5mqgZbRMw |archivedate = 2010-01-17|deadurl=no}}</ref> He later acknowledged that it had been a mistake to return to Brighton, and that he should have instead sought a fresh opportunity elsewhere.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Port-Vale-owe-club-huge-thanks-says-Adams/article-2132534-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: I owe club huge thanks, says Adams|date=8 May 2010|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=8 May 2010}}</ref>

===Port Vale===
[[File:Micky Adams.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Adams watching his team defeat [[Aldershot Town F.C.|Aldershot Town]] 1<U+2013>0 at [[Vale Park]] in September 2010.]]
In May 2009, Adams was a late applicant for the vacant manager's job at [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] after [[Dean Glover]]'s departure from the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8051739.stm|title=Adams is late entry for Vale job |date=15 May 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8079064.stm|title=Adams favourite for Port Vale job |date=2 June 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref> On 4 June, it was announced that Adams was to be appointed the new manager at [[Vale Park]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8082769.stm|title=Adams to be named Port Vale boss |date=4 June 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 June 2009}}</ref> His appointment was welcomed by the Vale players and supporters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-Richards-delighted-Adams-appointment/article-1052951-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Richards delighted by Adams appointment|date=5 June 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-Fans-Adams-appointment/article-1051993-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Fans back Adams appointment|date=5 June 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref> Chairman [[Bill Bratt]] stated that Adams' first goal  would be to stabilize the club,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-Adams-lead-Vale-revival-says-Bratt/article-1052683-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Adams can lead Vale revival, says Bratt|date=5 June 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref> a point reiterated by observers such as [[Robbie Earle]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Robbie-Earle-Adams-ideal-Vale-job/article-1052011-detail/article.html|title=Robbie Earle: Adams ideal for Vale job|date=5 June 2009 |work=The Sentinel|accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref> as well as Adams himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-m-man-revive-Vale-says-Adams/article-1053006-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: I'm the man to revive Vale, says Adams|date=5 June 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref> This followed the "Valiants" fall from [[Football League First Division|the second tier]] to near the bottom of [[the Football League]] within ten years.

He made his first signing on 15 June, bringing to the club on a [[free transfer (football)|free transfer]] a midfielder who had played for Adams at Brighton, 21 year old [[Tommy Fraser]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8101242.stm|title=Midfielder Fraser joins Port Vale |date=15 June 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> After confirming the signing of [[Adam Yates]], who was linked to the club before Adams' arrival, Adams signed [[Doug Loft]], who had also played under him at Brighton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Breaking-News-Port-Vale-complete-Loft-signing/article-1096404-detail/article.html|title=Breaking News: Port Vale complete Loft signing|date=22 June 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=22 June 2009}}</ref> After a pre-season [[exhibition game|friendly]], Adams considered switching to a 3<U+2013>5<U+2013>2 [[Formation (association football)|formation]] for the [[2009<U+2013>10 Port Vale F.C. season|2009<U+2013>10 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale/article-1178148-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Valiants beat Newcastle as boss Adams switches formation|last=Baggaley|first=Michael|date=20 July 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=20 July 2009}}</ref> Over his two spells in charge with the club he would switch between the 3<U+2013>5<U+2013>2 and 4<U+2013>4<U+2013>2 formations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14527694.stm|title=Sean Rigg impressed with new Port Vale formation|date=15 August 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref> On 21 July, it was announced that Adams had appointed veteran striker [[Geoff Horsfield]] as player-assistant manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Breaking-News-Port-Vale-appoint-Horsfield-assistant/article-1182630-detail/article.html|title=Breaking News: Port Vale appoint Horsfield as assistant|last=Baggaley |first=Michael|work=[[The Sentinel (Stoke-on-Trent)|The Sentinel]]|date=21 July 2009 |accessdate=31 July 2009}}</ref>

His first competitive game in charge was a 1<U+2013>1 draw with [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] on 8 August.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8186508.stm|title= Port Vale   1 <U+2013> 1   Rochdale|date=8 August 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 August 2009}}</ref> Three days later the club beat [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] 2<U+2013>1 at [[Bramall Lane]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] [[2009<U+2013>10 Football League Cup|First Round]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/8188418.stm|title= Sheff Utd   1 <U+2013> 2   Port Vale|date=11 August 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 August 2009|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5mqkXFLrW |archivedate = 2010-01-17|deadurl=no}}</ref> The solid opening day performance and especially the giant-slaying in the cup gave Vale fans great optimism for the season ahead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-manager-s-taking-Micky/article-1252185-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale fan zone: At last, a manager who's not taking the Micky|date=14 August 2009|last=Tideswell|first=Martin|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref> He was still strengthening his squad early in the season, signing midfielders [[Kris Taylor]] and [[Claus Bech J<U+00F8>rgensen]] on short-term deals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8189913.stm|title=Taylor signs short-term Vale deal|date=7 August 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=2009-08-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8200699.stm|title=Veteran Jorgensen signs for Vale |date=13 August 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=2009-08-16}}</ref> In order to raise cash he placed six youngsters on the transfer list.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-Valiants-transfer-list-players/article-1231046-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Valiants transfer list six players|last=Shaw|first=Steve|date=6 August 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=6 August 2009}}</ref> The Vale defeated [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] 2<U+2013>0 in the League Cup Second Round, with goals from Adams' signing Kris Taylor and [[Rob Taylor (footballer)|Rob Taylor]] <U+2013> a player not appreciated under Glover.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8221597.stm|title=Adams praises giant-killers Vale |date=26 August 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=26 August 2009}}</ref> It was only after the Wednesday game that Adams signed his managerial contract <U+2013> two months after taking charge.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8227879.stm|title=Adams signs one-year deal at Vale |date=28 August 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 August 2009}}</ref> The delay was blamed on "legal complications".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-Adams-signs-year-deal-club/article-1294859-detail/article.html#StartComments|title=Port Vale: Adams signs one-year deal with club|date=28 August 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=29 August 2009}}</ref> After a period of three defeats in seven days, including being knocked out of the League Cup at the Third Round, Adams decided to place his whole squad on the transfer list, saying of his team's performance: "We looked like a woman who had a big fur coat on but underneath she<U+2019>s got no knickers on."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-Adams-places-player-transfer-list/article-1371454-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Adams places every player on transfer list|last=Shaw|first=Steve|date=26 September 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=26 September 2009}}</ref> It was a controversial move, one that divided opinion among analysts and fans,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Lou-Macari-Nuclear-option-backfire-Adams/article-1373945-detail/article.html|title=Lou Macari: Nuclear option may backfire on Adams|last=Macari|first=Lou|date=29 September 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=1 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Robbie-Earle-Vale-boss-Adams-makes-shrewd/article-1381784-detail/article.html|title=Robbie Earle: Vale boss Adams makes shrewd move|last=Earle|first=Robbie|date=1 October 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=1 October 2009}}</ref> also bringing the fourth tier club to national attention.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/blog/2009/sep/29/micky-adams-port-vale-transfer-list|title=Micky Adams is playing a dangerous game at Port Vale|last=Taylor|first=Louise|work=The Guardian|accessdate=1 October 2009 | location=London | date=29 September 2009}}</ref> The move appeared to many to be a motivational tactic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-Motivation-transfer-listing-says-Adams/article-1400031-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Motivation was behind 'transfer-listing', says Adams|last=Shaw|first=Steve|date=8 October 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=8 October 2009}}</ref> He later admitted he merely played "a psychological game with them... [and] I don't think they fell for it <U+2013> I don't think anybody fell for it".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Rampant-Vale-slay-leaders-storm-play-places/article-2070072-detail/article.html|title=Rampant Vale slay the leaders to storm the play-off places|date=26 April 2010|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref> Three wins, including a [[Football League Trophy|cup]] win over League One [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] and a league win at local rivals [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]], and three draws within four weeks saw Adams nominated for the [[Football League Two Manager of the Month|League Two Manager of the Month]] award for October 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-Adams-united-says-Griffith/article-1482689-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Adams has united us, says Griffith|last=Shaw|first=Steve|date=5 November 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=5 November 2009}}</ref> He signed a contract extension in November 2009, keeping him at the club until summer 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Breaking-News-Adams-extends-Vale-stay/article-1495171-detail/article.html|title=Breaking News: Adams extends Vale stay|date=9 November 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=9 November 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.port-vale.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10381~1870297,00.html|title=Adams commits to three-year deal|date=9 November 2009|work=port-vale.co.uk|accessdate=9 November 2009}}</ref> His salary was believed to be around <U+00A3>65,000 a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Port-Vale-Adams-talking-terms-Blades-job/article-3051313-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Adams talking terms over Blades job|date=30 December 2010|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=30 December 2010}}</ref>

{{Quote|"The vision that I share with the board and the supporters is to win promotion. I think it can be achieved. It's all about short steps. The first one was to stabilise and we've done that. The players have bought into my philosophy and the next stage is to win promotion and establish ourselves as a [[Football League One|League One]] club."|Adams plans for the future at Vale Park future upon signing his two year contract extension.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8350785.stm|title=Adams extends Port Vale contract |date=9 November 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=9 November 2009}}</ref>}}

In the [[List of English football transfers winter 2009<U+2013>10|January 2010 transfer window]] he signed winger [[Lewis Haldane]] permanently, and took winger [[Sean Rigg]] and striker [[Craig Davies (footballer)|Craig Davies]] on loan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Vale-m-looking-late-transfer-deal-says-Adams/article-1782434-detail/article.html|title=Vale: I'm not looking for a late transfer deal says Adams|date=30 January 2010|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref> Adams' men stormed into the play-off places for the first time in the season with just two games left to play, following a 2<U+2013>1 win over champions-elect [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Phil-Sherwin-Micky-s-boys-roll-years/article-2070088-detail/article.html|title=Phil Sherwin: Micky's boys roll back the years|last=Sherwin|first=Phil|date=26 April 2010|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref> Yet with just one point from their final two games, the Vale finished the season in 10th place.

Before the start of the [[2010<U+2013>11 Port Vale F.C. season|2010<U+2013>11 season]] there was speculation that Adams would be approached by his former employers at Championship side [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], having impressed in his position at Port Vale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Port-Vale-Bratt-fazed-Adams-speculation/article-2352181-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Bratt not fazed by Adams speculation|date=28 June 2010|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref> Adams continued to make his mark at Vale though, releasing nine players, and signing Sean Rigg,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8708486.stm|title=Striker Sean Rigg signs two-year contract at Port Vale|date=27 May 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref> [[Stuart Tomlinson]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8720191.stm|title=New Port Vale goalkeeper Stuart Tomlinson 'has matured'|date=3 June 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 June 2010}}</ref> [[Justin Richards (footballer)|Justin Richards]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8729115.stm|title=Port Vale sign Cheltenham striker Justin Richards|date=11 June 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=14 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8782452.stm|title=Manager Micky Adams happy with Port Vale firepower|date=7 July 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 July 2010}}</ref> [[Ritchie Sutton]] and [[Gary Roberts (footballer born 1987)|Gary Roberts]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8831825.stm|title=Port Vale offer short-term deal to Ritchie Sutton|date=18 July 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 July 2010}}</ref> The season began similarly to the previous campaign, with a 3<U+2013>1 win at Championship side [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] in the [[2010<U+2013>11 Football League Cup|League Cup First Round]], new signing Richards scoring twice.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/8882713.stm|title=QPR   1 <U+2013> 3   Port Vale|date=10 August 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/8903569.stm|title=QPR win was no fluke, says Port Vale boss Micky Adams|date=11 August 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref> After his side won their opening four away league fixtures for the first time in their history,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Port-Vale-Adams-record-breakers-march/article-2662466-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Monday match report <U+2013> Macclesfield v Vale (PICS)|last=Shaw|first=Steve|date=20 September 2010|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=20 September 2010}}</ref> talks began to extend Adams' contract beyond 2012 as early as September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Bratt-wants-extend-phenomenal-Adams-stay/article-2662463-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Bill Bratt wants to extend 'phenomenal' Micky Adams' stay|last=Shaw|first=Steve|date=20 September 2010|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=20 September 2010}}</ref> Five wins in five for September saw Adam's gifted the [[Football League Two Manager of the Month|League Two Manager of the Month]] award,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.port-vale.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10381~2177530,00.html|title=Micky Wins Manager of the Month|date=7 October 2010|work=port-vale.co.uk|accessdate=7 October 2010}}</ref> his team also boasting five clean sheets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Port-Vale-Adams-hails-players-award-success/article-2735434-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Micky Adams hails players after award success|last=Shaw|first=Steve|date=8 October 2010|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=8 October 2010}}</ref> He was also handed the award for November, after his club advanced into the [[2010<U+2013>11 FA Cup|Third Round]] of the [[FA Cup]] and rose to the top of the [[Football League Two|League Two]] table on the back of five clean sheets in seven games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9273086.stm|title=Bristol City boss Millen named manager of the month|date=9 December 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=9 December 2010}}</ref> Departing for his boyhood club at the end of December 2010, he left the club in second position in League Two.<ref name="cn">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sheff_utd/9327422.stm|title=Micky Adams confirmed as Sheffield United manager|date=30 December 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 December 2010}}</ref>

===Sheffield United===
In December 2010, following [[Gary Speed]]'s departure from the job as manager of [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] for the position as the head coach of [[Wales national football team|Wales]], Adams was one of a handful of names linked to the vacant position at United. On [[Christmas Eve]], Vale chairman [[Bill Bratt]] announced he had "reluctantly" given Adams permission to talk to Sheffield United.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sheff_utd/9305847.stm|title=Sheffield United make Micky Adams approach <U+2013> Port Vale|date=24 December 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=24 December 2010}}</ref> Six days later it was announced that he would be taking the position,<ref name="cn" /> and he announced his three aims as manager would be to firstly avoid relegation, to then challenge for promotion, and finally "to develop a structure that will build us a reputation for home grown talent that fans can be proud of in their team".<ref name="cn" /> Former United player [[Alan Cork]] was installed as his assistant,<ref name="cn" /> Cork had worked as Adams' assistant at Fulham, Swansea, Leicester and Coventry. The fourth manager at the club [[2010<U+2013>11 Sheffield United F.C. season|that season]], he brought in [[Dave Bassett]] in a consultancy role after finding managing the club a bigger task than he had previously assumed.<ref name="slide">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/paulfletcher/2011/02/sheffield_united_on_the_slide.html#284156|title=Sheffield United on the slide|last=Fletcher|first=Paul|date=19 February 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> As Adams explained: "When you're manager at Port Vale you probably get three calls a day and one of those is from the wife asking me what time I'm coming home for my tea."<ref name="slide" /> His honeymoon period dissipated quickly, as United failed to win in his first eleven games in charge (four draws and seven defeats) and slipped into 23rd spot after letting slip a two goal lead to lose 3<U+2013>2 to fellow relegation strugglers [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/9402118.stm|title=Scunthorpe   3 <U+2013> 2   Sheff Utd|date=22 February 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> Adams told the press that "The fans were singing 'you're not fit to wear the shirt', I cannot disagree with them. That is as disappointing a result as I have ever had in my career."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sheff_utd/9405871.stm|title=Micky Adams expects more from Sheffield United players |date=23 February 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> It took three months before he achieved his first win. The victory came on 8 March 2011 (his fourteenth game in charge), as his side came from behind to beat [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] 2<U+2013>1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/9415424.stm|title=Sheff Utd   2 <U+2013> 1   Nott'm Forest|date=8 March 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> Sheffield United were relegated to [[Football League One|League One]] at the end of the season, finishing six points short of safety. Adams and United parted company after a meeting with owner [[Kevin McCabe (businessman)|Kevin McCabe]]. McCabe stated that he wished to initiate a "clean sweep at the top and start afresh"; whilst Adams said that whilst he was "very, very disappointed with the decision... I am a Blade and will always be a Blade."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/13354375.stm|title=Sheffield United sack Micky Adams|date=10 May 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref>

===Return to Port Vale===
After losing his job at [[Bramall Lane]], he was immediately offered a three year contract at former club Port Vale.<ref name="pvoff">{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/9482906.stm|title=Port Vale offer Micky Adams manager position |accessdate=2011-05-11|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 May 2011}}</ref> He signed the contract within days, saying it was time to "finish the job I started".<ref name="back">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/vale/portvalenews/Port-Vale/article-3555018-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Micky Adams is back to finish the job he started|accessdate=2011-05-13|date=13 May 2011|author=steve shaw|work=The Sentinel}}</ref> Upon hearing the news, star defender [[Gareth Owen (footballer born 1982)|Gareth Owen]] reversed his decision to leave the club, and promptly signed a two year deal as player-coach.<ref name="back"/> Following an [[Extraordinary General Meeting]] at the club in which two of the club's five directors were voted off, Adams' transfer plans were disrupted as the club's constitution stipulated that at least four directors must be in place for financial transactions such as issuing new contracts to take place.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1394530/Port-Vale-boss-Micky-Adams-targets-directorship-club.html|title=Port Vale boss Micky Adams targets directorship in order to use his own money for transfers|date=5 June 2011|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=5 June 2011}}</ref> In a shock move Adams announced that he intended to take up a directorship at the club, and after being sponsored onto the board through the support of former director Stan Meigh, he was quoted as saying that "this is a purely footballing decision... I understand that the last few months have been difficult for everyone and am asking all of our supporters to put their differences aside, to support my candidacy for the Board and then to get behind the team in the coming season."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.port-vale.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10381~2371762,00.html|title=Micky announces candidacy to become a director|date=5 June 2011|work=port-vale.co.uk|accessdate=5 June 2011}}</ref> Supporters' groups opposed to [[Bill Bratt]]'s chairmanship did not welcome the news.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/vale/portvalenews/Port-Vale-Supporters-hit-Adams-board-announcement/article-3629697-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: Supporters hit out at Adams' board announcement|date=6 June 2011|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=6 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/9505457.stm|title=Port Vale boss Micky Adams announces director candidacy |date=6 June 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 June 2011}}</ref> However shareholders voted him onto the board.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/9516027.stm|title=Manager Micky Adams eligible to join Port Vale board |date=17 June 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 June 2011}}</ref> His first signings of the season were former [[Glenn Hoddle Academy]] youngsters [[Ryan Burge]] and [[Ben Williamson (footballer)<U+200E>|Ben Williamson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/9524455.stm|title=Ben Williamson and Ryan Burge join Port Vale |date=28 June 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=28 June 2011}}</ref> He followed this by tying [[Gary Roberts (footballer born 1987)|Gary Roberts]] to the club for another season, and signing [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] centre-half [[Clayton McDonald]], left-back [[Mike Green (footballer born 1989)|Mike Green]], and Sheffield United teenagers [[Kingsley James]] and [[Phil Roe (footballer)|Phil Roe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/port_vale/9528029.stm|title=Port Vale agree deals with Sheffield United duo |date=1 July 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 July 2011}}</ref> Days before the start of [[2011<U+2013>12 Port Vale F.C. season|the season]] he let [[Justin Richards (footballer)|Justin Richards]] leave on a free transfer to [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14322974.stm|title=Burton Albion sign Justin Richards and Tom Parkes|date=28 July 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 July 2011}}</ref> and replaced him with [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] striker [[Tom Pope]], also a free transfer signing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14365621.stm|title=Port Vale sign ex-Rotherham striker Tom Pope|date=2 August 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 August 2011}}</ref> After his team started the campaign with a glut of goals <U+2013> both scoring and conceding <U+2013> Adams decided to give his players "a kick up the backside" by signing experienced defenders [[Liam Chilvers]] (on loan) and [[Robert Kozluk]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Port-Vale-Adams-makes-double-signing-Crewe-game/story-13390087-detail/story.html|title=Port Vale: Adams makes double signing for Crewe game|date=23 September 2011|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref>

==Personal life==
His mother was a [[Cook (servant)|cook]] and his father was a [[Steel mill|steelworker]]; he grew up with two sisters and one brother; his brother suffers from [[cerebral palsy]].<ref name="up close" />

He has three daughters from his first marriage; the marriage broke down during his time at [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], due in part to the amount of time he was putting into his football career.<ref name="up close" /> He later married Claire, with whom he had daughter Madison, born around 2004.<ref name="could have" />

Adams made an appearance on [[BBC Radio Leicester]]'s version of ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' in August 2004, and chose songs from [[Nat King Cole]] (''[[Love Letters (song)|Love Letters]]''), [[Billy Joel]] (''[[Scenes from an Italian Restaurant]]''), [[The Style Council]] (''[[Shout to the Top!]]''), and [[INXS]] (''[[Mystify (song)|Mystify]]'').<ref name="up close" />

